# create a connection
pw <- {"ya_password"}
# loads the PostgreSQL driver

# creates a connection to the postgres database
# note that "con" will be used later in each connection to the database

SELECT DISTINCT

In a table, a column can contain duplicate values, and sometimes you only want distinct, or unique, values. the SELECT DISTINCT statement gets all

SELECT DISTINCT release_year FROM film;
SELECT DISTINCT actor FROM actor;
SELECT DISTINCT rental_rate FROM film;
SELECT DISTINCT rental_rate FROM film;
3 records
rental_rate
2.99
4.99
0.99

SELECT DISTINCT CHALLENGE

We want to know the types of ratings movies can get in the United states, such as PG, PG-13, etc. We want to know the types of rating types the movies in our database can have.

SELECT DISTINCT rating FROM film;
5 records
rating
NC-17
G
PG
PG-13
R

So there’s G, PG, PG-13, R, and NC-17. Looks like all the ratings are covered in this database of movies.

SELECT WHERE

We already know how to query data from a table in a database. BUt what if we want to query just particular rows form a table matching some sort of condition? Use the WHERE clause in the SELECT statement.

Example: SELECT column_1, column_2… column_n WHERE conditions;

The conditions are used to filter the rows returned from the SELECT statement.

So if you want to get all customers whose names are jamie, you can use the WHERE with the = operator like so:

SELECT last_name, first_name FROM customer WHERE first_name = 'Jamie';
2 records
last_name first_name
Rice Jamie
Waugh Jamie

Imagine you want to select a customer whose first_name is jamie and whose last_name is rice.

SELECT last_name, first_name FROM customer WHERE first_name = 'Jamie' AND last_name = 'Rice';
1 records
last_name first_name
Rice Jamie

Imagine you want to know who paid a rental amount either less than $1 or greater than $8, you can use the OR operator.

SELECT customer_id, amount, payment_date FROM payment WHERE amount <= 1 OR amount >= 8;

Let’s play around a lil.

SELECT email FROM customer 
WHERE first_name = 'Jared';
-- note the variable you condition on, WHERE first_name = 'Jared', doesn't have to be in the return variable you select
SELECT * from payment 
WHERE amount = 7.99;
-- let's explore a few more logical operators
SELECT * FROM payment 
WHERE amount <5;

SELECT * FROM payment 
WHERE amount <= 4.99;

SELECT amount, payment_date FROM payment WHERE amount != 4.99;
-- returns all columns where amounts are not equal to 4.99

The AND operator allows us to combine multiple conditions

SELECT * from CUSTOMER WHERE store_id = 1 AND address_id > 5;
SELECT * FROM CUSTOMER WHERE store_id = 1 OR store_id = 2;
--of course, we can't use AND everywhere, like if it doesn't make sense:
SELECT * FROM customer WHERE store_id = 1 AND store_id = 2;
-- we can't do this because an observation won't have a store id of both 1 and 2 - it doesn't make sense.

COUNT

The COUNT function returns the number of input rows that match a specific condition of a query. Basically it counts the rows where the condition is true.

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM address;
SELECT COUNT(phone) FROM address;
1 records
count
603

Keep in mind that COUNT does not consider NULL values in the column. We can also do SELECT DISTINCT FOR EXAMPLE:

SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT COLUMN) FROM TABLE; and that will count the number of particular rows for that column.

COUNT is a very fast function.

SELECT COUNT(*) FROM payment;
SELECT * FROM payment;
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT amount) FROM payment;
SELECT COUNT(DISTINCT(amount)) FROM payment; -- parentheses also work
-- counting the DISTINCT amount types from the payment table
1 records
count
19

We’ll revisit COUNT a lot and it’s going to be useful when we learn GROUP BY clauses.

LIMIT

LIMIT allows you to limit the number of rows you get back after a query. Useful when wanting to get many columns, but now many rows. It works well by placing it at the end of a query.

SELECT title, description, release_year, length, rating  FROM film LIMIT 3;
3 records
title description release_year length rating
Chamber Italian A Fateful Reflection of a Moose And a Husband who must Overcome a Monkey in Nigeria 2006 117 NC-17
Grosse Wonderful A Epic Drama of a Cat And a Explorer who must Redeem a Moose in Australia 2006 49 R
Airport Pollock A Epic Tale of a Moose And a Girl who must Confront a Monkey in Ancient India 2006 54 R

ORDER

When you query data from a table, PostGRESQL returns rows in the order that they were inserted into the table. If you want to sort the resulting set, you can use the ORDER BY clause in conjunction with the SELECT statement. The ORDER BY clause allows you to sort the rows returned from the SELECT statement in ascending or descending order based on criteria specified.

SELECT title, description, release_year, length FROM FILM ORDER BY title ASC LIMIT 10;
SELECT title, description, release_year, length FROM FILM ORDER BY title DESC LIMIT 10;
Displaying records 1 - 10
title description release_year length
Zorro Ark A Intrepid Panorama of a Mad Scientist And a Boy who must Redeem a Boy in A Monastery 2006 50
Zoolander Fiction A Fateful Reflection of a Waitress And a Boat who must Discover a Sumo Wrestler in Ancient China 2006 101
Zhivago Core A Fateful Yarn of a Composer And a Man who must Face a Boy in The Canadian Rockies 2006 105
Youth Kick A Touching Drama of a Teacher And a Cat who must Challenge a Technical Writer in A U-Boat 2006 179
Young Language A Unbelieveable Yarn of a Boat And a Database Administrator who must Meet a Boy in The First Manned Space Station 2006 183
Yentl Idaho A Amazing Display of a Robot And a Astronaut who must Fight a Womanizer in Berlin 2006 86
Wyoming Storm A Awe-Inspiring Panorama of a Robot And a Boat who must Overcome a Feminist in A U-Boat 2006 100
Wrong Behavior A Emotional Saga of a Crocodile And a Sumo Wrestler who must Discover a Mad Cow in New Orleans 2006 178
Wrath Mile A Intrepid Reflection of a Technical Writer And a Hunter who must Defeat a Sumo Wrestler in A Monastery 2006 176
Worst Banger A Thrilling Drama of a Madman And a Dentist who must Conquer a Boy in The Outback 2006 185

And interesting here, we learn there is a movie named ‘Zorro Ark’, which is likely where the name of the Pokémon Zoroark comes from.

Specify the column that you want to sort in the ORDER BY clause. If you sort the result set by multiple columns, use a comma to separate between two columns. If you leave it blank, it uses ASC by default.

SELECT first_name, last_name FROM customer ORDER BY first_name ASC;
SELECT first_name, last_name FROM customer ORDER BY first_name ASC, last_name DESC;
Displaying records 1 - 10
first_name last_name
Aaron Selby
Adam Gooch
Adrian Clary
Agnes Bishop
Alan Kahn
Albert Crouse
Alberto Henning
Alex Gresham
Alexander Fennell
Alfred Casillas

So this last query sorts the first_name column in ascending order, and the last_name column in descending order. So your results are FIRST being sorted by the first names, so you’re going to start with Aarons and go to Zekes. But also, if there’s Aaron Zoroak and Aaron Yveltal, you’re going to get Aaron Zoroark before Aaron Yveltal.

Postgresql also allows you to sort by columns even if they’re not selected. Other ANSI SQL formats may not let you do this. Most standard sql queries will only allow you to sort rows that appear in the SELECT clause.

SELECT first_name, last_name FROM customer ORDER BY last_name;
Displaying records 1 - 10
first_name last_name
Rafael Abney
Nathaniel Adam
Kathleen Adams
Diana Alexander
Gordon Allard
Shirley Allen
Charlene Alvarez
Lisa Anderson

Ida Andrews
